      "question": "A vertical pole of height $h$ stands on level ground. At a point $P$ on the ground, the angle of elevation of the top of the pole is $30^\\circ$. If the point $P$ is moved $20$ $m$ closer to the base of the pole, the angle of elevation becomes $60^\\circ$. The height $h$ of the pole in meters is given by:",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Let the height of the pole be $h$ and the distance from $P$ to the base be $x$.",
          "From the first triangle, $\\tan 30^\\circ = \\frac{h}{x} \\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} = \\frac{h}{x} \\Rightarrow x = h\\sqrt{3}$.",
          "After moving $20$ $m$ closer, the new distance is $x - 20$. In the second triangle, $\\tan 60^\\circ = \\frac{h}{x - 20} \\Rightarrow \\sqrt{3} = \\frac{h}{x - 20}$.",
          "Substitute $x = h\\sqrt{3}$ into the second equation: $\\sqrt{3} = \\frac{h}{h\\sqrt{3} - 20}$.",
          "Solve for $h$: $h = \\sqrt{3}(h\\sqrt{3} - 20) \\Rightarrow h = 3h - 20\\sqrt{3} \\Rightarrow 2h = 20\\sqrt{3} \\Rightarrow h = 10\\sqrt{3}$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$h = x \\tan 30^\\circ \\Rightarrow x = h \\sqrt{3} \\\\ h = (x - 20) \\tan 60^\\circ \\\\ h = (h \\sqrt{3} - 20) \\sqrt{3} \\\\ h = 3h - 20 \\sqrt{3} \\\\ 2h = 20 \\sqrt{3} \\\\ h = 10 \\sqrt{3}$"
      },
